  <div class="post">
    <main class="post-wrapper">
      <DetailHeader tag="UX PROJECT" description="Jan–Apr 2021">
        <h1 class="font-type">Manse</h1>
        <p class="project-subtitle">Feedback Bot Manse — A Human‑Centered AI Feedback Channel for the Smart City</p>
      </DetailHeader>

      <section class="manse-content">
        <!-- 01. Project Overview -->
        <div class="content-section first">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">01</span>
            <h2>Project Overview</h2>
          </div>
          <p class="intro-paragraph"><strong>Feedback Bot Manse</strong> is an AI‑infused chatbot for the smart city of Tampere, designed to provide a positive, transparent, and seamless feedback experience. Residents can report municipal issues (e.g., broken streetlights, icy roads, missing traffic signs) or offer suggestions. The project followed a Human‑Centered Design process grounded in in‑depth research, structured ideation, and multiple rounds of prototype validation.</p>

          <h3 class="subsection-heading">The Problem</h3>
          <p>Citizens often notice areas for improvement but don’t submit feedback—channels are unclear, the process feels cumbersome, and people fear their input will be ignored. Existing methods (like the website form) are hard to find, lack essentials such as photo upload and precise location tagging, and rarely provide follow‑up—discouraging engagement.</p>

          <h3 class="subsection-heading">Our Solution</h3>
          <p>We designed <strong>Manse</strong>, an AI‑powered chatbot that understands natural language, guides users through reporting, auto‑categorizes issues, and routes them to the correct municipal department. It also sends status updates to build trust. The long‑term vision is a pervasive, multilingual, multi‑channel feedback system for the city.</p>

          <h3 class="subsection-heading">My Role</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>User Research:</strong> Co‑planned and conducted 6 semi‑structured interviews; synthesized findings via affinity diagramming.</li>
            <li><strong>Ideation:</strong> Co‑created personas and journey maps; contributed to team brainstorming and concept refinement.</li>
            <li><strong>Prototyping & Validation:</strong> Three iterative MVP validation rounds; built hi‑fi Figma prototypes; optimized via user testing.</li>
            <li><strong>Documentation & Presentation:</strong> Contributed to weekly learning diaries and the final presentation.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- 02. Design Process (reference layout: clear phases + steps) -->
        <div class="content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">02</span>
            <h2>Design Process</h2>
          </div>
          <h3 class="phase-heading">Phase 1 — Discover & Define</h3>
          <p>The initial phase was dedicated to deep research to understand the stakeholders, the existing ecosystem, and most importantly, the citizens' needs and frustrations. We aimed to answer the question: "Why aren't citizens actively providing feedback?"</p>
          
          <h4 class="step-heading">1. Stakeholder Analysis & System Research</h4>
          <p>We began by mapping all stakeholders on a Power/Interest Grid. This exercise confirmed that **citizens** were our primary focus group due to their high interest and influence. We also tested the city's current feedback channels (website form vs. email) and discovered that timely responses and a transparent process are critical for building user trust.</p>
          <figure class="figure">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e216abfd2fc4828dd61efb_Screen_Shot_2021-02-04_at_11.28.01_AM.png" alt="Power/Interest Grid for Stakeholder Prioritization" />
            <figcaption>Power/Interest Grid for stakeholder prioritization</figcaption>
          </figure>
                   <figure class="figure">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e216977b4a0a40bf6ea56e_Screen_Shot_2021-02-26_at_13.16.37.png" alt="Value Proposition Canvas" />
            <figcaption>Value Proposition Canvas—linking pains to gains</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <h4 class="step-heading">2. User Interviews & Affinity Diagramming</h4>
          <p>We conducted 6 in-depth, semi-structured interviews with Tampere residents to uncover their experiences and motivations. The rich qualitative data was then synthesized collaboratively using an Affinity Diagram. This process was crucial as it allowed us to cluster hundreds of individual observations into core themes and surface four critical insights that drove our entire design direction:</p>
          <div class="highlight-box">
            <ul class="insights-list">
              <li><strong>Bystander Effect:</strong> Many people assumed someone else had already reported an issue, so they didn't act.</li>
              <li><strong>Lack of Trust:</strong> A pervasive feeling that their feedback would be ignored or would not make a difference.</li>
              <li><strong>Channel Confusion:</strong> Users were often unsure which person or department to contact for specific issues.</li>
              <li><strong>Need for Confirmation:</strong> A fundamental desire to receive confirmation that their report had been received and was being processed.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
            <figure class="figure">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e2d69adc72a16fe101c768_Untitled%20(2).png" alt="Affinity Diagram" />
            <figcaption>Affinity Diagram—synthesizing interview insights</figcaption>
          </figure>
          
          <h3 class="phase-heading">Phase 2 — Develop & Deliver</h3>
          <p>Armed with clear insights from our research, we moved into the solution space. This phase was all about translating user needs into tangible design concepts through personas, journey mapping, and iterative, user-centered validation.</p>
          
          <h4 class="step-heading">1. Personas & User Journey Mapping</h4>
          <p>To humanize our data and focus our design, we created two key personas. Our primary focus became **Matti, the "Passive Citizen,"** who cares about the city but is deterred by the inconvenient and opaque feedback process. We then created a detailed user journey map for Matti, which visually exposed the key moments of friction and negative emotion, particularly the difficulty of finding the right channel and the frustrating silence while waiting for a response. This map became our guide for identifying the most critical opportunities for improvement.</p>
         <figure class="figure">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e2d68651c920084e8d166b_User_Journey.png" alt="User Journey Map" />
            <figcaption>User Journey Map highlighting pain points</figcaption>
          </figure>
          
          <h4 class="step-heading">2. Prototyping & Iterative Validation</h4>
          <p>We followed a rapid prototyping approach, conducting three distinct rounds of validation to test and refine our concept with real users. This iterative cycle was essential for correcting our assumptions and ensuring the final product was truly usable and valuable.</p>
          <ul class="validation-rounds">
            <li><strong>Round 1 — Typeform (Low-fi):</strong> We built a simple prototype using Typeform to quickly validate the core logic and conversational flow of the chatbot interaction. This allowed us to test the basic concept without investing heavily in visual design.</li>
            <li><strong>Round 2 — Figma (Hi-fi):</strong> Based on initial feedback, we created a high-fidelity prototype in Figma. This version focused on refining the conversational UX and establishing a clear visual interface. Users responded positively to the more natural dialogue and clear guidance.</li>
            <li><strong>Round 3 — Figma Refined:</strong> A key learning from Round 2 was that users were confused by the AI-suggested "popular issue" tags. In this final iteration, we clarified the copy and added a prominent "My problem is not in the list" option. This small change significantly boosted usability and user confidence.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- 03. The Final Solution -->
        <div class="content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">03</span>
            <h2>The Final Solution</h2>
          </div>
          <ul class="feature-list-min">
            <li><strong>Natural Conversational Experience:</strong> Manse uses Natural Language Processing (NLP) to understand user input and guides them with well-structured questions to gather all necessary details (description, photos, location).</li>
            <li><strong>Multi‑Modal Input:</strong> The chatbot supports text, voice messages, image attachments, and map-based location sharing to accommodate various user needs and contexts.</li>
            <li><strong>Transparent Process Tracking:</strong> After submitting feedback, users receive a confirmation and can track the status of their issue, including which department is handling it, which greatly enhances trust.</li>
            <li><strong>Intelligent Routing:</strong> The AI can automatically categorize feedback and route it to the correct municipal department, improving the city's operational efficiency.</li>
            <li><strong>Helpful, Friendly Tone:</strong> Manse's conversational tone is designed to be warm, supportive, and understanding, aiming to create a positive emotional experience for citizens.</li>
          </ul>
